  <discussion>No Atrichum species occurring in North America has been as widely misunderstood as A. undulatum.  Evidently introduced from Europe, its weedy habitat and strongly arcuate, almost horizontal capsules are the surest means of recognition.  Variety minus, a fixture of European manuals, is a stunted form that is highly variable and possibly a hybrid.  Its occurrence in North America has not been demonstrated.  As used by American authors (e.g., O. E. Jennings 1951), it probably refers to A. altecristatum.</discussion>
